# Clean evolution, no legacy overlays

When implementing any non-trivial change, do not stack new logic on top of outdated logic just to preserve the old structure.

Goal:
the codebase must evolve cleanly.
New functionality must not create architectural growths, overlapping flows, parallel truth, or legacy layers that stay only because they were already there.

Principles:

- Do not add a new layer, wrapper, flag branch, duplicate handler, alternative flow, compatibility path, or special-case patch if the underlying model is no longer correct.
- If the new feature changes the meaning, lifecycle, ownership, or invariants of an existing part of the system, refactor the affected core design in that bounded area instead of adding a surface workaround.
- Prefer one clean explicit flow over multiple partially overlapping flows.
- Prefer replacing obsolete structure over preserving it out of fear.
- Prefer deletion of outdated code over indefinite coexistence.
- Do not keep dead branches, obsolete DTOs, duplicate services, old validation paths, legacy mappers, or shadow state after the new design is introduced.
- Do not preserve old architecture only for historical reasons.

Mandatory decision before coding:

For each serious change, first determine which of the two cases is true:

1. Extension case:
   the existing core model is still correct, and the new requirement is a true extension.
   Then extend through the existing boundaries in the simplest clean way.

2. Core-change case:
   the new requirement changes the actual domain model, state model, ownership, lifecycle, or main processing flow.
   Then update the affected core design and remove or migrate the outdated structure instead of layering on top of it.

Implementation rules:

- If the change affects core domain meaning, state transitions, ownership of truth, or the main system flow, do not implement it as a patch around the old core.
- Refactor the touched bounded context until the result is coherent and readable as one design.
- Delete or migrate outdated code in the touched area in the same task when it is safe and justified.
- Keep the blast radius controlled, but do not artificially protect obsolete local design.
- Do not introduce speculative abstractions, generic engines, or framework-heavy redesign just to "clean things up".
- Clean evolution means correct simplification, not a vanity rewrite.

Required review output before implementation:

For serious changes, explicitly state:
- what is changing in the domain or flow
- whether this is an extension case or a core-change case
- which old parts become obsolete
- what should be deleted, merged, or rewritten
- why a patch-on-top approach would create legacy growth

Required final result:

After implementation, the touched area must have:
- one clear source of truth
- one clear ownership model
- one clear flow for the changed behavior
- no duplicate competing paths for the same business outcome
- no obsolete code left behind without justification

Required summary after implementation:

Always summarize:
- what was changed in the design
- what old structure was removed or merged
- what was intentionally not preserved
- why the resulting design is cleaner than a layered patch
